05117nam a22006615i 9780822382119DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19971997ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223821197 a10.1515/97808223821192doi  a(DE-B1597)553894  a(OCoLC)1125826919  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPT363.N27bZ36 1997 7aHIS0140002bisacsh04a830.9/3582211 aZantop, Susanne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aColonial Fantasies :bConquest, Family, and Nation in Precolonial Germany, 1770-1870 /cSusanne Zantop; Stanley Fish, Fredric Jameson. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1997] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b9 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI Armchair Conquistadors; or, The Quest for "New Germany" -- t1 Tiranos animales 0 alemanes: Germans and the "Conquest" -- t2 A Conquest of the Intellect -- tII Colonizing Theory: Gender, Race, and the Search for a National Identity -- t3 Gendering the "Conquest" -- t4 Racializing the Colony -- t5 Patagons and Germans -- tIII Colonial Families; or, Displacing the Colonizers -- t6 Fathers and Sons: Donnerstag and Freitag, Campe and Krusoe -- t7 Husbands and Wives: Colonialism Domesticated -- t8 Betrothal and Divorce; or, Revolution in the House -- tIV Virgin Islands, Teuton Conquerors -- t9 The German Columbus -- t10 The Second Discovery -- t11 Colonial Fantasies Revisited -- tEpilogue: Vitzliputzli's Revenge -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince Germany became a colonial power relatively late, postcolonial theorists and histories of colonialism have thus far paid little attention to it. Uncovering Germany's colonial legacy and imagination, Susanne Zantop reveals the significance of colonial fantasies-a kind of colonialism without colonies-in the formation of German national identity. Through readings of historical, anthropological, literary, and popular texts, Zantop explores imaginary colonial encounters of "Germans" with "natives" in late-eighteenth- and early-nineteenth-century literature, and shows how these colonial fantasies acted as a rehearsal for actual colonial ventures in Africa, South America, and the Pacific.From as early as the sixteenth century, Germans preoccupied themselves with an imaginary drive for colonial conquest and possession that eventually grew into a collective obsession. Zantop illustrates the gendered character of Germany's colonial imagination through critical readings of popular novels, plays, and travel literature that imagine sexual conquest and surrender in colonial territory-or love and blissful domestic relations between colonizer and colonized. She looks at scientific articles, philosophical essays, and political pamphlets that helped create a racist colonial discourse and demonstrates that from its earliest manifestations, the German colonial imagination contained ideas about a specifically German national identity, different from, if not superior to, most others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aColonies in literature. 0aFamilies in literature. 0aGerman literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aImperialismxHistoryy19th century. 0aMilitary history in literature. 0aNational characteristics, German, in literature. 0aNationalism in literature. 0aNationalismzGermanyxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh1 aFish, Stanley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.